{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 11:01:27.697645", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Summary\n- Overall control-plane and server-side connectivity appears healthy: core/distribution routers are advertising server networks, servers and load-balancer can reach each other and the DNS, and host_1 has full network connectivity.\n- One clear anomaly: host_2_1_1_1 has no IP address and cannot reach the server/DNS (reachability tests for that host are unknown/failed).\n- Localization and root cause: the DHCP server configuration lacks a subnet/pool for the 10.2.1.0/24 network (the network served by router_dist_2_1). This explains why host_2 did not obtain an address.\n\nEvidence and findings (data extracted from the environment)\n\n1) Reachability matrix (selected results)\n- Many intra-server and server-to-infrastructure pings are OK (examples):\n  - dhcp_server -> web_server_1: 0% loss, RTT avg 2.233 ms\n  - load_balancer -> web_server_1: 0% loss, RTT avg 0.975 ms\n  - web_server_0 -> dns_server: 0% loss, RTT avg 0.979 ms\n- host_1_1_1_1 -> web_server_1 and -> dns_server: OK (0% loss, RTTs ~2–3 ms)\n- host_2_1_1_1 -> web_server_1 and -> dns_server: status \"unknown\" in the reachability output (no tx/rx results), indicating the probing could not be performed/replied.\n\n2) Host 2 interface state\n- host_2_1_1_1 ifconfig / ip addr:\n  - eth0 is UP (flags include UP, RUNNING, LOWER_UP), but there is no IPv4 address assigned (ip_addr output shows only link-layer, no inet entry).\n  - ifconfig counters show RX/TX packets — link is physically up and seeing traffic, but no DHCP lease was applied.\n\n3) Switch / local layer\n- switch_access_2_1_1 shows br0 and eth1 present and UP, with RX/TX packet counts, indicating the access switch port and bridge are operational and carrying traffic between host_2 and the distribution router.\n\n4) Distribution router (router_dist_2_1) config and routing\n- router_dist_2_1 br0 has IP 10.2.1.1/24 — this is the expected gateway for hosts in 10.2.1.0/24.\n- router_dist_2_1 ip_route shows 10.2.1.0/24 is present locally and OSPF is in use (it also has routes to 10.1.1.0 and 10.200.0.0 via OSPF).\n- FRR running config on router_dist_2_1 includes:\n  - network 10.2.1.0/24 area 1\n  - network 172.16.0.8/31 area 1\n  -> So routing is present and the dist router is advertising/connected to 10.2.1.0/24.\n\n5) DHCP server configuration\n- /etc/dhcp/dhcpd.conf (dhcp_server) contains:\n  - subnet 10.1.1.0 netmask 255.255.255.0 { range 10.1.1.10 10.1.1.100; option routers 10.1.1.1; option domain-name-servers 10.200.0.2; }\n  - subnet 10.200.0.0 netmask 255.255.255.0 { # pass }\n- There is NO subnet declaration for 10.2.1.0/24 (the network served by router_dist_2_1).\n- Host_1 (10.1.1.10) did receive a DHCP address from the configured 10.1.1.0 pool; host_2 (on 10.2.1.0/24) did not receive an address.\n\nLogical analysis tying the evidence together\n- Host_2's NIC and access switch are operational (interfaces UP, packets seen), and the distribution router is present and advertising 10.2.1.0/24 — this reduces likelihood of a physical link, switch, or routing problem for the 10.2.1.0/24 subnet.\n- The DHCP server has no scope for 10.2.1.0/24, so when host_2 requests an address there is no matching pool to hand out a lease. That explains the absence of an IPv4 address on host_2 and the reachability probe failures for that host.\n- Other services (DNS, web, load-balancer) are reachable from host_1 and from servers, indicating OSPF and inter-subnet routing/forwarding are functioning for configured networks.\n\nLocalization of the fault\n- Primary faulty component: dhcp_server (configuration) — specifically, missing DHCP subnet declaration/pool for 10.2.1.0/24.\n- Affected devices/networks: host_2_1_1_1 (10.2.1.x host), and any other hosts in the 10.2.1.0/24 subnet that require DHCP leases.\n\nOther observations (non-fault)\n- OSPF appears to be functioning and distributing server/subnet routes (router_dist_2_1 shows OSPF networks and routes).\n- Server farm internal connectivity and DNS responses appear healthy from server-side tests.\n- Load balancer can reach backends and DNS.\n\nRecommended next information to collect (diagnostic, not remedial)\n- DHCP server logs during host_2 boot/lease request (e.g., /var/log/syslog or dhcpd logs) to confirm DHCPDISCOVER for 10.2.1.0 and the server behavior.\n- A packet capture on host_2 or on switch_access_2_1_1 eth1 to confirm DHCPDISCOVER/Offer traffic is seen and whether the DHCP server replies.\n- Confirm relay/bootp-relay config if DHCP requests are supposed to be relayed from router_dist_2_1 — check if ip helper/relay is configured (if relay is required in this topology).\n- Verify whether other 10.2.1.x hosts (if any) have addresses or similar symptoms.\n\nClosing statement\n- The network is largely healthy except for a DHCP provisioning gap affecting the 10.2.1.0/24 subnet. The most likely root cause is the DHCP server configuration missing a subnet/pool for 10.2.1.0/24, resulting in host_2 not obtaining an IPv4 address despite link and routing being up.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 8322, "output_tokens": 2367, "total_tokens": 10689, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 7808}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 960}}}
